afterload causes enhanced calcium release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum","Decreased preload triggers release of natriuretic peptides"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased preload leads to greater myocardial fiber stretch and stronger contractions\u003C/strong\u003E through the Frank-Starling mechanism. When venous return increases, the ventricles fill with more blood (increased preload), stretching the cardiac muscle fibers. This stretch optimizes the overlap between actin and myosin filaments, leading to stronger contractions and increased stroke volume.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased afterload causes enhanced calcium release\u003C/strong\u003E - While afterload affects contractility, this is not the Frank-Starling mechanism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESympathetic stimulation increases heart rate and contractility\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes beta-adrenergic effects, not the Frank-Starling mechanism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased preload triggers release of natriuretic peptides\u003C/strong\u003E - Natriuretic peptides are released with stretch, not decreased preload\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased coronary blood flow enhances myocardial contractility\u003C/strong\u003E - While coronary flow is important for function, this is not the Frank-Starling mechanism\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Frank-Starling mechanism allows the heart to automatically adjust cardiac output to match venous return on a beat-to-beat basis without needing neural or hormonal input.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Frank-Starling mechanism describes how increased ventricular filling leads to increased stroke volume via enhanced myocardial fiber stretch.","Increased preload causes greater sarcomere stretch, optimizing actin-myosin overlap and increasing force of contraction."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52801"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16858"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52801"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T22:59:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T23:00:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9548"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67349"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4903"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Ca